I use Tcl for a number of analysis scripts inside some scientific software. Recently, I came across a situation in which I had nested loops:<p><pre><code>    for {set i 0} {$i<$n} {incr i} {
        # Some comment
        for {set j 0} {$j<$n} {incr j} {
</code></pre>
The script refused to run and eventually I figured out that the comment was somehow impeding execution. I still don't understand why.

Actually, I think its syntax isn't just simple, it's simplistic.  It's simple to implement, but it presents some rather unexpected behaviour to the user.  To wit:<p><pre><code>  proc hello {} {
    # I'd like to put an unmatched { in my comment
    puts "Hello!"
  }
</code></pre>
This doesn't compile because of the unmatched {.<p>But this does, by adding another unmatched } - in the following string:<p><pre><code>  proc hello {} {
    # I'd like to put an unmatched { in my comment
    puts "Hello!}"
  }

</code></pre>
In other news, Richard P. Gabriel can stop arguing with himself about whether worse is better.  In this case, worse is pretty silly!
